| I/B/14\n| [[Johann Christoph Bach]]\n| ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Lieber Herre Gott, wecke uns auf|scores|3=Lieber Herr Gott, wekke uns auf (Bach, Johann Christoph)}}''\n| [[motet]]\n| [[SATB|SATB+SATB]] [[Woodwind instrument|Ww]]s [[String instrument|Str]]s [[basso continuo|Bc]]\n| {{BD0|9092|0}}\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"650\" | deest\n| I/B/17\n| [[Johann Christoph Bach]]\n| ''Unsers Herzens Freude hat ein Ende''\n| [[motet]]\n| [[SATB|SATB+SATB]] [[basso continuo|Bc]]\n| {{BD0|9119|0}}\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"700\" | deest\n| \u2014\n| [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] ([[Johann Christoph Bach]]?)\n| ''[[BWV 1164|Ich lasse dich nicht, du segnest mich denn]]'' ([[BWV]] 1164 = [[BWV Anh.]] 159)\n| [[motet]]\n| [[SATB|SATB+SATB]]\n| {{BD0|1470|0}}\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"750\" | deest\n| \u2014\n| [[Johann Christoph Bach]]\n| ''F\u00fcrchte dich nicht, denn ich hab dich erl\u00f6st''\n| [[motet]]\n| [[SATB|SATTB]] [[basso continuo|Bc]]\n| {{BD0|9850|0}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite journal\n| last = Melamed\n| first = Daniel R.\n| title = The Authorship of the Motet ''Ich lasse dich nicht'' (BWV&nbsp;Anh.&nbsp;159)\n| url = https://jams.ucpress.edu/content/41/3/491.full.pdf+html\n| year = 1988\n| journal = [[Journal of the American Musicological Society]]\n| others = [[American Musicological Society]]\n| publisher = [[University of California Press]]\n| volume = 41\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 491\u2013526\n| jstor = 831462\n| doi = 10.2307/831462 \n| ref = harv }}\n* Axel Fischer and Matthias Kornemann (editors). [http://www.degruyter.com/view/product/41788 ''The Archive of the Sing-Akademie zu Berlin: Catalogue''.] De Gruyter, 2009. {{ISBN|978-3-598-11798-5}}.\n* [[Max Schneider (music historian)|Max Schneider]] (editor). ''Altbachisches Archiv: aus Johann Sebastian Bachs Sammlung von Werken seiner Vorfahren Johann, Heinrich, Georg Christoph, Johann Michael u. Johann Christoph Bach.'' (Das Erbe deutscher Musik, Series I). Breitkopf & H\u00e4rtel, Leipzig 1935, reprint 1966.\n** Vol. 1: [http://d-nb.info/1001795741 ''Motetten und Chorlieder''.]\n** Vol. 2: [http://d-nb.info/1001796136 ''Kantaten''.]\n* Patrice Veit. [http://ifha.revues.org/624 \"''EN\u00dfLIN, Wolfram,'' Die Bach-Quellen der SingAkademie zu Berlin. Katalog\"], recension in ''Revue de l'Institut fran\u00e7ais d'histoire en Allemagne'', 2007.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/AltBachische-CantusColln.htm Das Alt-Baschische Archiv \u2013 Performed by Konrad J\u00fcnghanel & Cantus C\u00f6lln] at {{url|www.bach-cantatas.com}}\n\n{{Bach family}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by members of the Bach family| ]]\n[[Category:Vocal musical compositions]]\n[[Category:Motets]]\n[[Category:Cantatas]]\n[[Category:17th century in music]]\n", "text_old": "'''{{lang|de|Altbachisches Archiv}}''', also '''{{lang|de|Alt-Bachische Archiv}}''' ('''ABA''', old-Bachian archive), is a collection of 17th-century vocal music, most of which was written by members of the [[Bach family]].\n\n==History==\n[[Johann Ambrosius Bach]], [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Johann Sebastian]]'s father, supposedly started to collect compositions by his relatives. [[Bach's Nekrolog|Johann Sebastian Bach's obituary]] starts with an overview of the composers whose works are contained in the {{lang|de|Altbachisches Archiv}}. [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach]], Johann Sebastian's son and co-author of his obituary, retained the collection and gave it its name. After his death the largest part of the collection came, via {{Interlanguage link multi|Georg P\u00f6lchau|de|3=Georg Poelchau|lt=Georg P\u00f6lchau}}, in the possession of the [[Sing-Akademie zu Berlin]]. All nine motets of the Sing-Akademie's part of the ABA collection, including [[BWV&nbsp;1164]], at the time attributed to [[Johann Christoph Bach]], were published in the early 1820s.{{sfn|Melamed|1988|pp=495\u2013498}}\n\nThe manuscripts of two compositions contained in the Sing-Akademie's part of the ABA collection were sold to the Royal Library in Berlin (later renamed as [[Berlin State Library]]): thus [[List of compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach#BNB|BNB]]&nbsp;I/B/11 and BWV&nbsp;1164 were no longer in the Sing-Akademie's archives by the end of the 19th century.{{sfn|Melamed|1988|pp=497\u2013498}} In 1935 [[Max Schneider (music historian)|Max Schneider]], recovering ABA manuscripts scattered in the Sing-Akademie's archive,{{sfn|Melamed|1988|pp=495\u2013496}} published a selection of these compositions, an edition which was reprinted in 1966.<ref>Schneider 1935/1966</ref> ABA numbers derive from this publication in two volumes.<ref>Schneider 1935/1966</ref> The original manuscripts of the Sing-Akademie's archive went lost during the [[Second World War]],{{sfn|Melamed|1988|p=496}} only to be rediscovered in [[Ukraine]] in 1999, after which they were returned to the Sing-Akademie, which in turn deposited the recovered manuscripts in the Berlin State Library for conservation.<ref>Fischer/Kornemann, 2009</ref>\n\n==Compositions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Altbachisches Archiv\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | ABA\n! scope=\"col\" | BNB\n! scope=\"col\" | Composer\n! scope=\"col\" | Composition\n! scope=\"col\" | Genre\n! scope=\"col\" | Scoring\n! scope=\"col\" | [[List of compositions by Johann Sebastian Bach#BD|BDW]]\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"101\" | I, 1\n| I/An/11\n| [[Johannes Bach]] {{nobreak|([[Johann Michael Bach]]?)}}\n| ''Sei nun wieder zufrieden''\n| [[motet]] ([[aria]])\n| [[SATB|SSAT+ATTB]] [[basso continuo|Bc]]\n| {{BD0|8736|0}}\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"102\" | I, 2\n| I/B/43\n| [[Johannes Bach]] {{nobreak|([[Johann Michael Bach]]?)}}\n| ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Unser Leben ist ein Schatten|scores|3=Unser Leben ist ein Schatten (Bach, Johann)|lt=Unser Leben ist ein Schatten}}''\n| [[motet]]\n| [[SATB|SSATTB+ATB]]\n| {{BD0|8740|0}}\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"103\" | I, 3\n| I/An/12\n| [[Johannes Bach]]\n| ''Weint nicht um meinen Tod''\n| [[motet]] ([[aria]]