ton Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] <br> <small>(11 May 2003, [[FA Premier League|Premier League]])</small>\n| lowest attendance  = 29,359 vs [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] <br> <small>(4 Feb 2003, [[FA Cup]])</small>\n| average attendance = 37,768\n| pattern_la1        = \n| pattern_b1         = \n| pattern_ra1        = \n| pattern_sh1        = \n| pattern_so1        = \n| leftarm1           = \n| body1              = \n| rightarm1          = \n| shorts1            = \n| socks1             = \n| pattern_la2        = \n| pattern_b2         = \n| pattern_ra2        = \n| pattern_sh2        = \n| pattern_so2        = \n| leftarm2           = \n| body2              = \n| rightarm2          = \n| shorts2            = \n| socks2             = \n| pattern_la3        = \n| pattern_b3         = \n| pattern_ra3        = \n| pattern_sh3        = \n| pattern_so3        = \n| leftarm3           = \n| body3              = \n| rightarm3          = \n| shorts3            = \n| socks3             = \n| prevseason         = [[2001\u201302 Leeds United A.F.C. season|2001\u201302]]\n| nextseason         = [[2003\u201304 Leeds United A.F.C. season|2003\u201304]]\n}}\n\nThe [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303 season]] saw Leeds United compete in the Premier League (known as the Barclaycard Premiership for sponsorship reasons).\n\n==Season summary==\nDespite much anticipation with the arrival of new manager Terry Venables and an impressive start with four wins in six including back to back wins over Newcastle and Manchester United form begun to drop adding pressure to Terry Venables, United's debts also began racking up, the club began selling many first-team players to raise money, most notably defender and captain [[Rio Ferdinand]], sold to arch-rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for around 30 million pounds - a world record for a defender at the time. The mass exodus of players leaving (which forced many youth players like [[James Milner]] and [[Matthew Kilgallon]] into the first team) despite reaching the quarter finals of the FA cup were Leeds lost to Sheffield United Terry Venables left the club with 8 games left and with former Sunderland manager Peter Reid appointed Leeds sealed a disappointing 15th place largely thanks to striker [[Mark Viduka]]. Viduka struck 20 goals in the Premiership alone, making him the fourth highest scorer in the league that season. [[Harry Kewell]] was also influential, scoring 14 on his own and setting up several of Viduka's strikes, before departing to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the summer, but Leeds financial worries were only just beginning.\n\n==Final league table==\n{{main|2002\u201303 FA Premier League}}\n{{:2002\u201303 FA Premier League|showteam=LEE}}\n\n==Kit==\n[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] remained as Leeds United's kit sponsors, and introduced a new home kit for the season.\n\n==First-team squad==\n<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/eng/2002-2003/faprem/leeds.htm | title=Leeds United - 2002/03 | publisher=FootballSquads | accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref>\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Nigel Martyn]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=2|nat=IRL|pos=DF|name=[[Gary Kelly (footballer born 1974)|Gary Kelly]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|nat=IRL|pos=DF|name=[[Ian Harte]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|nat=FRA|pos=MF|name=[[Olivier Dacourt]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=RSA|pos=DF|name=[[Lucas Radebe]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Michael Bridges]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=AUS|pos=FW|name=[[Mark Viduka]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=AUS|pos=FW|name=[[Harry Kewell]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=ESP|pos=MF|name=[[Ra\u00fal Bravo]]|other=on loan from [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=ENG|pos=MF|name=[[Nick Barmby]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=ENG|pos=GK|name=[[Paul Robinson (footballer, born 1979)|Paul Robinson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=IRL|pos=MF|name=[[Stephen McPhail]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=SWE|pos=DF|name=[[Teddy Lu\u010di\u0107]]|other=on loan from [[AIK Fotboll|A